#: ../../extending/first-extension-module.rst:9
msgid "Your first C API extension module"
msgstr ""

#: ../../extending/first-extension-module.rst:11
msgid ""
"This tutorial will take you through creating a simple Python extension "
"module written in C or C++."
msgstr ""

#: ../../extending/first-extension-module.rst:14
msgid ""
"We will use the low-level Python C API directly. For easier ways to create "
"extension modules, see the :ref:`recommended third party tools <c-api-"
"tools>`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../extending/first-extension-module.rst:18
msgid ""
"The tutorial assumes basic knowledge about Python: you should be able to "
"define functions in Python code before starting to write them in C. See :ref:"
"`tutorial-index` for an introduction to Python itself."
msgstr ""

#: ../../extending/first-extension-module.rst:22
msgid ""
"The tutorial should be approachable for anyone who can write a basic C "
"library. While we will mention several concepts that a C beginner would not "
"be expected to know, like ``static`` functions or linkage declarations, "
"understanding these is not necessary for success."
msgstr ""

#: ../../extending/first-extension-module.rst:27
msgid ""
"We will focus on giving you a \"feel\" of what Python's C API is like. It "
"will not teach you important concepts, like error handling and reference "
"counting, which are covered in later chapters."
msgstr ""

#: ../../extending/first-extension-module.rst:31
msgid ""
"We will assume that you use a Unix-like system (including macOS and Linux), "
"or Windows. On other systems, you might need to adjust some details -- for "
"example, a system command name."
msgstr ""

#: ../../extending/first-extension-module.rst:36
msgid ""
"You need to have a suitable C compiler and Python development headers "
"installed. On Linux, headers are often in a package like ``python3-dev`` or "
"``python3-devel``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../extending/first-extension-module.rst:40
msgid ""
"You need to be able to install Python packages. This tutorial uses `pip "
"<https://pip.pypa.io/>`__ (``pip install``), but you can substitute any tool "
"that can build and install ``pyproject.toml``-based projects, like `uv "
"<https://docs.astral.sh/uv/>`_ (``uv pip install``). Preferably, have a :ref:"
"`virtual environment <venv-def>` activated."
msgstr ""

#: ../../extending/first-extension-module.rst:49
msgid ""
"This tutorial uses APIs that were added in CPython 3.15. To create an "
"extension that's compatible with earlier versions of CPython, please follow "
"an earlier version of this documentation."
msgstr ""

#: ../../extending/first-extension-module.rst:53
msgid ""
"This tutorial uses C syntax added in C11 and C++20. If your extension needs "
"to be compatible with earlier standards, please follow tutorials in "
"documentation for Python 3.14 or below."
msgstr ""

#: ../../extending/first-extension-module.rst:59
msgid "What we'll do"
msgstr ""

#: ../../extending/first-extension-module.rst:61
msgid ""
"Let's create an extension module called ``spam`` [#why-spam]_, which will "
"include a Python interface to the C standard library function :c:func:"
"`system`. This function is defined in ``stdlib.h``. It takes a C string as "
"argument, runs the argument as a system command, and returns a result value "
"as an integer. A manual page for :c:func:`system` might summarize it this "
"way::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../extending/first-extension-module.rst:69
msgid ""
"#include <stdlib.h>\n"
"int system(const char *command);"
msgstr ""

#: ../../extending/first-extension-module.rst:72
msgid ""
"Note that like many functions in the C standard library, this function is "
"already exposed in Python. In production, use :py:func:`os.system` or :py:"
"func:`subprocess.run` rather than the module you'll write here."
msgstr ""

#: ../../extending/first-extension-module.rst:77
msgid "We want this function to be callable from Python as follows:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../extending/first-extension-module.rst:79
msgid ""
">>> import spam\n"
">>> status = spam.system(\"whoami\")\n"
"User Name\n"
">>> status\n"
"0"
msgstr ""

#: ../../extending/first-extension-module.rst:89
msgid ""
"The system command ``whoami`` prints out your username. It's useful in "
"tutorials like this one because it has the same name on both Unix and "
"Windows."
msgstr ""

#: ../../extending/first-extension-module.rst:95
msgid "Start with the headers"
msgstr ""

#: ../../extending/first-extension-module.rst:97
msgid ""
"Begin by creating a directory for this tutorial, and switching to it on the "
"command line. Then, create a file named :file:`spammodule.c` in your "
"directory. [#why-spammodule]_"
msgstr ""

#: ../../extending/first-extension-module.rst:102
msgid ""
"In this file, we'll include two headers: :file:`Python.h` to pull in all "
"declarations of the Python C API, and :file:`stdlib.h` for the :c:func:"
"`system` function. [#stdlib-h]_"
msgstr ""

#: ../../extending/first-extension-module.rst:106
msgid "Add the following lines to :file:`spammodule.c`:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../extending/first-extension-module.rst:108
msgid ""
"#include <Python.h>\n"
"#include <stdlib.h>     // for system()\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../extending/first-extension-module.rst:112
msgid ""
"Be sure to put :file:`stdlib.h`, and any other standard library includes, "
"*after* :file:`Python.h`. On some systems, Python may define some pre-"
"processor definitions that affect the standard headers."
msgstr ""

#: ../../extending/first-extension-module.rst:119
msgid "Running your build tool"
msgstr ""

#: ../../extending/first-extension-module.rst:121
msgid ""
"With only the includes in place, your extension won't do anything. Still, "
"it's a good time to compile it and try to import it. This will ensure that "
"your build tool works, so that you can make and test incremental changes as "
"you follow the rest of the text."
msgstr ""

#: ../../extending/first-extension-module.rst:126
msgid ""
"CPython itself does not come with a tool to build extension modules; it is "
"recommended to use a third-party project for this. In this tutorial, we'll "
"use `meson-python`_. (If you want to use another one, see :ref:`first-"
"extension-other-tools`.)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../extending/first-extension-module.rst:135
msgid "``meson-python`` requires defining a \"project\" using two extra files."
msgstr ""

#: ../../extending/first-extension-module.rst:137
msgid "First, add ``pyproject.toml`` with these contents:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../extending/first-extension-module.rst:139
msgid ""
"[build-system]\n"
"build-backend = 'mesonpy'\n"
"requires = ['meson-python']\n"
"\n"
"[project]\n"
"# Placeholder project information\n"
"# (change this before distributing the module)\n"
"name = 'sampleproject'\n"
"version = '0'"
msgstr ""

#: ../../extending/first-extension-module.rst:151
msgid "Then, create ``meson.build`` containing the following:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../extending/first-extension-module.rst:153
msgid ""
"project('sampleproject', 'c')\n"
"\n"
"py = import('python').find_installation(pure: false)\n"
"\n"
"py.extension_module(\n"
"   'spam',          # name of the importable Python module\n"
"   'spammodule.c',  # the C source file\n"
"   install: true,\n"
")"
msgstr ""

#: ../../extending/first-extension-module.rst:167
msgid ""
"See `meson-python documentation <meson-python>`_ for details on "
"configuration."
msgstr ""

#: ../../extending/first-extension-module.rst:170
msgid ""
"Now, build install the *project in the current directory* (``.``) via "
"``pip``:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../extending/first-extension-module.rst:172
msgid "python -m pip -v install ."
msgstr ""

#: ../../extending/first-extension-module.rst:176
msgid ""
"The ``-v`` (``--verbose``) option causes ``pip`` to show the output from the "
"compiler, which is often useful during development."
msgstr ""

#: ../../extending/first-extension-module.rst:181
msgid ""
"If you don't have ``pip`` installed, run ``python -m ensurepip``, preferably "
"in a :ref:`virtual environment <venv-def>`. (Or, if you prefer another tool "
"that can build and install ``pyproject.toml``-based projects, use that.)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../extending/first-extension-module.rst:189
msgid ""
"Note that you will need to run this command again every time you change your "
"extension. Unlike Python, C has an explicit compilation step."
msgstr ""

#: ../../extending/first-extension-module.rst:193
msgid ""
"When your extension is compiled and installed, start Python and try to "
"import it. This should fail with the following exception:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../extending/first-extension-module.rst:197
msgid ""
">>> import spam\n"
"Traceback (most recent call last):\n"
"   ...\n"
"ImportError: dynamic module does not define module export function "
"(PyModExport_spam or PyInit_spam)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../extending/first-extension-module.rst:206
msgid "Module export hook"
msgstr ""

#: ../../extending/first-extension-module.rst:208
msgid ""
"The exception you got when you tried to import the module told you that "
"Python is looking for a \"module export function\", also known as a :ref:"
"`module export hook <extension-export-hook>`. Let's define one."
msgstr ""

#: ../../extending/first-extension-module.rst:213
msgid "First, add a prototype below the ``#include`` lines:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../extending/first-extension-module.rst:215
msgid ""
"\n"
"PyMODEXPORT_FUNC PyModExport_spam(void);\n"
"\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../extending/first-extension-module.rst:220
msgid ""
"The prototype is not strictly necessary, but some modern compilers emit "
"warnings without it. It's generally better to add the prototype than to "
"disable the warning."
msgstr ""

#: ../../extending/first-extension-module.rst:224
msgid ""
"The :c:macro:`PyMODEXPORT_FUNC` macro declares the function's return type, "
"and adds any special linkage declarations needed to make the function "
"visible and usable when CPython loads it."
msgstr ""

#: ../../extending/first-extension-module.rst:228
msgid ""
"After the prototype, add the function itself. For now, make it return "
"``NULL``:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../extending/first-extension-module.rst:231
msgid ""
"PyMODEXPORT_FUNC\n"
"PyModExport_spam(void)\n"
"{\n"
"   return NULL;\n"
"}"
msgstr ""

#: ../../extending/first-extension-module.rst:239
msgid ""
"Compile and load the module again. You should get a different error this "
"time."
msgstr ""

#: ../../extending/first-extension-module.rst:242
msgid ""
">>> import spam\n"
"Traceback (most recent call last):\n"
"   ...\n"
"SystemError: module export hook for module 'spam' failed without setting an "
"exception"
msgstr ""

#: ../../extending/first-extension-module.rst:249
msgid ""
"Simply returning ``NULL`` is *not* correct behavior for an export hook, and "
"CPython complains about it. That's good -- it means that CPython found the "
"function! Let's now make it do something useful."
msgstr ""

#: ../../extending/first-extension-module.rst:256
msgid "The slot table"
msgstr ""

#: ../../extending/first-extension-module.rst:258
msgid ""
"Rather than ``NULL``, the export hook should return the information needed "
"to create a module. Let's start with the basics: the name and docstring."
msgstr ""

#: ../../extending/first-extension-module.rst:262
msgid ""
"The information should be defined in an array of :c:type:`PySlot` entries, "
"which are essentially key-value pairs. Define this array just before your "
"export hook:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../extending/first-extension-module.rst:266
msgid ""
"PyABIInfo_VAR(abi_info);\n"
"\n"
"static PySlot spam_slots[] = {\n"
"   PySlot_STATIC_DATA(Py_mod_abi, &abi_info),\n"
"   PySlot_STATIC_DATA(Py_mod_name, \"spam\"),\n"
"   PySlot_STATIC_DATA(Py_mod_doc, \"A wonderful module with an example "
"function\"),\n"
"   PySlot_END\n"
"};"
msgstr ""

#: ../../extending/first-extension-module.rst:277
msgid ""
"The :c:macro:`PySlot_STATIC_DATA` macro is used when the slot value (here: "
"``&abi_info``, ``\"spam\"``, and the docstring) is a pointer to constant, "
"statically allocated data."
msgstr ""

#: ../../extending/first-extension-module.rst:281
msgid ""
"The ``PyABIInfo_VAR(abi_info);`` macro and the :c:data:`Py_mod_abi` slot are "
"a bit of boilerplate that helps prevent extensions compiled for a different "
"version of Python from crashing the interpreter."
msgstr ""

#: ../../extending/first-extension-module.rst:285
msgid ""
"For both :c:data:`Py_mod_name` and :c:data:`Py_mod_doc`, the values are C "
"strings -- that is, NUL-terminated, UTF-8 encoded byte arrays."
msgstr ""

#: ../../extending/first-extension-module.rst:288
msgid ""
"Note ``PySlot_END`` sentinel entry at the end. This marks the end of the "
"array. If you forget it, you'll trigger undefined behavior."
msgstr ""

#: ../../extending/first-extension-module.rst:292
msgid ""
"The array is defined as ``static`` -- that is, not visible outside this ``."
"c`` file. This will be a common theme. CPython only needs to access the "
"export hook; all global variables and all other functions should generally "
"be ``static``, so that they don't clash with other extensions."
msgstr ""

#: ../../extending/first-extension-module.rst:298
msgid "Return this array from your export hook instead of ``NULL``:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../extending/first-extension-module.rst:300
msgid ""
"PyMODEXPORT_FUNC\n"
"PyModExport_spam(void)\n"
"{\n"
"   return spam_slots;\n"
"}"
msgstr ""

#: ../../extending/first-extension-module.rst:309
msgid "Now, recompile and try it out:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../extending/first-extension-module.rst:311
msgid ""
">>> import spam\n"
">>> print(spam)\n"
"<module 'spam' from '/home/encukou/dev/cpython/spam.so'>"
msgstr ""

#: ../../extending/first-extension-module.rst:317
msgid "You have an extension module! Try ``help(spam)`` to see the docstring."
msgstr ""

#: ../../extending/first-extension-module.rst:320
msgid "The next step will be adding a function."
msgstr ""

#: ../../extending/first-extension-module.rst:326
msgid "Exposing a function"
msgstr ""

#: ../../extending/first-extension-module.rst:328
msgid ""
"To expose the :c:func:`system` C function directly to Python, we'll need to "
"write a layer of glue code to convert arguments from Python objects to C "
"values, and the C return value back to Python."
msgstr ""

#: ../../extending/first-extension-module.rst:332
msgid ""
"One of the simplest ways to write glue code is a \":c:data:`METH_O`\" "
"function, which takes two Python objects and returns one. All Python objects "
"-- regardless of the Python type -- are represented in C as pointers to the :"
"c:type:`PyObject` structure."
msgstr ""

#: ../../extending/first-extension-module.rst:337
msgid "Add such a function above the slots array::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../extending/first-extension-module.rst:339
msgid ""
"static PyObject *\n"
"spam_system(PyObject *self, PyObject *arg)\n"
"{\n"
"   Py_RETURN_NONE;\n"
"}"
msgstr ""

#: ../../extending/first-extension-module.rst:345
msgid ""
"For now, we ignore the arguments, and use the :c:macro:`Py_RETURN_NONE` "
"macro, which expands to a ``return`` statement that properly returns a "
"Python :py:data:`None` object."
msgstr ""

#: ../../extending/first-extension-module.rst:349
msgid ""
"Recompile your extension to make sure you don't have syntax errors. We "
"haven't yet added ``spam_system`` to the module, so you might get a warning "
"that ``spam_system`` is unused."
msgstr ""

#: ../../extending/first-extension-module.rst:356
msgid "Method definitions"
msgstr ""

#: ../../extending/first-extension-module.rst:358
msgid ""
"To expose the C function to Python, you will need to provide several pieces "
"of information in a structure called :c:type:`PyMethodDef` [#why-"
"pymethoddef]_:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../extending/first-extension-module.rst:362
msgid "``ml_name``: the name of the Python function;"
msgstr ""

#: ../../extending/first-extension-module.rst:363
msgid "``ml_doc``: a docstring;"
msgstr ""

#: ../../extending/first-extension-module.rst:364
msgid "``ml_meth``: the C function to be called; and"
msgstr ""

#: ../../extending/first-extension-module.rst:365
msgid ""
"``ml_flags``: a set of flags describing details like how Python arguments "
"are passed to the C function. We'll use :c:data:`METH_O` here -- the flag "
"that matches our ``spam_system`` function's signature."
msgstr ""

#: ../../extending/first-extension-module.rst:370
msgid ""
"Because modules typically create several functions, these definitions need "
"to be collected in an array, with a zero-filled sentinel at the end. Add "
"this array just below the ``spam_system`` function:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../extending/first-extension-module.rst:374
msgid ""
"\n"
"static PyMethodDef spam_methods[] = {\n"
"    {\n"
"        .ml_name=\"system\",\n"
"        .ml_meth=spam_system,\n"
"        .ml_flags=METH_O,\n"
"        .ml_doc=\"Execute a shell command.\",\n"
"    },\n"
"    {NULL, NULL, 0, NULL}        /* Sentinel */\n"
"};\n"
"\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../extending/first-extension-module.rst:378
msgid ""
"As with module slots, a zero-filled sentinel marks the end of the array."
msgstr ""

#: ../../extending/first-extension-module.rst:380
msgid ""
"Next, we'll add the method to the module. Add a :c:data:`Py_mod_methods` "
"slot to your :c:type:`PyMethodDef` array:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../extending/first-extension-module.rst:383
msgid ""
"\n"
"PyABIInfo_VAR(abi_info);\n"
"\n"
"static PySlot spam_slots[] = {\n"
"    PySlot_STATIC_DATA(Py_mod_abi, &abi_info),\n"
"    PySlot_STATIC_DATA(Py_mod_name, \"spam\"),\n"
"    PySlot_STATIC_DATA(Py_mod_doc, \"A wonderful module with an example "
"function\"),\n"
"    PySlot_STATIC_DATA(Py_mod_methods, spam_methods),\n"
"    PySlot_END\n"
"};\n"
"\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../extending/first-extension-module.rst:388
msgid ""
"Recompile your extension again, and test it. Be sure to restart the Python "
"interpreter, so that ``import spam`` picks up the new version of the module."
msgstr ""

#: ../../extending/first-extension-module.rst:392
msgid "You should now be able to call the function:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../extending/first-extension-module.rst:394
msgid ""
">>> import spam\n"
">>> print(spam.system)\n"
"<built-in function system>\n"
">>> print(spam.system('whoami'))\n"
"None"
msgstr ""

#: ../../extending/first-extension-module.rst:402
msgid ""
"Note that our ``spam.system`` does not yet run the ``whoami`` command; it "
"only returns ``None``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../extending/first-extension-module.rst:405
msgid ""
"Check that the function accepts exactly one argument, as specified by the :c:"
"data:`METH_O` flag:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../extending/first-extension-module.rst:408
msgid ""
">>> print(spam.system('too', 'many', 'arguments'))\n"
"Traceback (most recent call last):\n"
"   ...\n"
"TypeError: spam.system() takes exactly one argument (3 given)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../extending/first-extension-module.rst:417
msgid "Returning an integer"
msgstr ""

#: ../../extending/first-extension-module.rst:419
msgid ""
"Now, let's take a look at the return value. Instead of ``None``, we'll want "
"``spam.system`` to return a number -- that is, a Python :py:type:`int` "
"object. Eventually this will be the exit code of a system command, but let's "
"start with a fixed value, say, ``3``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../extending/first-extension-module.rst:425
msgid ""
"The Python C API provides a function to create a Python :py:type:`int` "
"object from a C ``int`` value: :c:func:`PyLong_FromLong`. [#why-"
"pylongfromlong]_"
msgstr ""

#: ../../extending/first-extension-module.rst:428
msgid "To call it, replace the ``Py_RETURN_NONE`` with the following 3 lines:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../extending/first-extension-module.rst:432
msgid ""
"static PyObject *\n"
"spam_system(PyObject *self, PyObject *arg)\n"
"{\n"
"   int status = 3;\n"
"   PyObject *result = PyLong_FromLong(status);\n"
"   return result;\n"
"}"
msgstr ""

#: ../../extending/first-extension-module.rst:444
msgid ""
"Recompile, restart the Python interpreter again, and check that the function "
"now returns 3:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../extending/first-extension-module.rst:447
msgid ""
">>> import spam\n"
">>> spam.system('whoami')\n"
"3"
msgstr ""

#: ../../extending/first-extension-module.rst:455
msgid "Accepting a string"
msgstr ""

#: ../../extending/first-extension-module.rst:457
msgid "Finally, let's handle the function argument."
msgstr ""

#: ../../extending/first-extension-module.rst:459
msgid ""
"Our C function, :c:func:`!spam_system`, takes two arguments. The first one, "
"``PyObject *self``, will be set to the ``spam`` module object. This isn't "
"useful in our case, so we'll ignore it."
msgstr ""

#: ../../extending/first-extension-module.rst:464
msgid ""
"The other one, ``PyObject *arg``, will be set to the object that the user "
"passed from Python. We expect that it should be a Python string. In order to "
"use the information in it, we will need to convert it to a C value -- in "
"this case, a C string (``const char *``)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../extending/first-extension-module.rst:470
msgid ""
"There's a slight type mismatch here: Python's :py:class:`str` objects store "
"Unicode text, but C strings are arrays of bytes. So, we'll need to *encode* "
"the data, and we'll use the UTF-8 encoding for it. (UTF-8 might not always "
"be correct for system commands, but it's what :py:meth:`str.encode` uses by "
"default, and the C API has special support for it.)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../extending/first-extension-module.rst:477
msgid ""
"The function to encode a Python string into a UTF-8 buffer is named :c:func:"
"`PyUnicode_AsUTF8AndSize` [#why-pyunicodeasutf8]_. Call it like this:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../extending/first-extension-module.rst:481
msgid ""
"static PyObject *\n"
"spam_system(PyObject *self, PyObject *arg)\n"
"{\n"
"   const char *command = PyUnicode_AsUTF8AndSize(arg, NULL);\n"
"   int status = 3;\n"
"   PyObject *result = PyLong_FromLong(status);\n"
"   return result;\n"
"}"
msgstr ""

#: ../../extending/first-extension-module.rst:493
msgid ""
"If :c:func:`PyUnicode_AsUTF8AndSize` is successful, *command* will point to "
"the resulting C string -- a zero-terminated array of bytes [#embedded-nul]_. "
"This buffer is managed by the *arg* object, which means we don't need to "
"free it, but we must follow some rules:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../extending/first-extension-module.rst:498
msgid ""
"We should only use the buffer inside the ``spam_system`` function. After "
"``spam_system`` returns, *arg* and the buffer it manages might be garbage-"
"collected."
msgstr ""

#: ../../extending/first-extension-module.rst:501
msgid "We must not modify it. This is why we use ``const``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../extending/first-extension-module.rst:503
msgid ""
"If :c:func:`PyUnicode_AsUTF8AndSize` was *not* successful, it returns a "
"``NULL`` pointer. When calling *any* Python C API, we always need to handle "
"such error cases. The way to do this in general is left for later chapters "
"of this documentation. For now, be assured that we are already handling "
"errors from :c:func:`PyLong_FromLong` correctly."
msgstr ""

#: ../../extending/first-extension-module.rst:510
msgid ""
"For the :c:func:`PyUnicode_AsUTF8AndSize` call, the correct way to handle "
"errors is returning ``NULL`` from ``spam_system``. Add an ``if`` block for "
"this:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../extending/first-extension-module.rst:515
msgid ""
"static PyObject *\n"
"spam_system(PyObject *self, PyObject *arg)\n"
"{\n"
"   const char *command = PyUnicode_AsUTF8AndSize(arg);\n"
"   if (command == NULL) {\n"
"      return NULL;\n"
"   }\n"
"   int status = 3;\n"
"   PyObject *result = PyLong_FromLong(status);\n"
"   return result;\n"
"}"
msgstr ""

#: ../../extending/first-extension-module.rst:530
msgid ""
"To test that error handling works, compile again, restart Python so that "
"``import spam`` picks up the new version of your module, and try passing a "
"non-string value to your function:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../extending/first-extension-module.rst:534
msgid ""
">>> import spam\n"
">>> spam.system(3)\n"
"Traceback (most recent call last):\n"
"   ...\n"
"TypeError: bad argument type for built-in operation"
msgstr ""

#: ../../extending/first-extension-module.rst:542
msgid ""
"Now, all that is left is calling the C library function :c:func:`system` "
"with the ``char *`` buffer, and using its result instead of the ``3``:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../extending/first-extension-module.rst:545
msgid ""
"static PyObject *\n"
"spam_system(PyObject *self, PyObject *arg)\n"
"{\n"
"   const char *command = PyUnicode_AsUTF8AndSize(arg);\n"
"   if (command == NULL) {\n"
"      return NULL;\n"
"   }\n"
"   int status = system(command);\n"
"   PyObject *result = PyLong_FromLong(status);\n"
"   return result;\n"
"}"
msgstr ""

#: ../../extending/first-extension-module.rst:560
msgid ""
"Compile your module, restart Python, and test. This time, you should see "
"your username -- the output of the ``whoami`` system command:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../extending/first-extension-module.rst:564
msgid ""
">>> import spam\n"
">>> result = spam.system('whoami')\n"
"User Name\n"
">>> result\n"
"0"
msgstr ""

#: ../../extending/first-extension-module.rst:572
msgid ""
"You can also test with other commands, like ``ls``, ``dir``, or one that "
"doesn't exist:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../extending/first-extension-module.rst:575
msgid ""
">>> import spam\n"
">>> result = spam.system('nonexistent-command')\n"
"sh: line 1: nonexistent-command: command not found\n"
">>> result\n"
"32512"
msgstr ""

#: ../../extending/first-extension-module.rst:585
msgid "The result"
msgstr ""

#: ../../extending/first-extension-module.rst:588
msgid ""
"Congratulations! You have written a complete Python C API extension module, "
"and completed this tutorial!"
msgstr ""

#: ../../extending/first-extension-module.rst:592
msgid "Here is the entire source file, for your convenience:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../extending/first-extension-module.rst:596
msgid ""
"/// Includes\n"
"\n"
"#include <Python.h>\n"
"#include <stdlib.h>     // for system()\n"
"\n"
"/// Implementation of spam.system\n"
"\n"
"static PyObject *\n"
"spam_system(PyObject *self, PyObject *arg)\n"
"{\n"
"   const char *command = PyUnicode_AsUTF8AndSize(arg, NULL);\n"
"   if (command == NULL) {\n"
"      return NULL;\n"
"   }\n"
"   int status = system(command);\n"
"   PyObject *result = PyLong_FromLong(status);\n"
"   return result;\n"
"}\n"
"\n"
"/// Module method table\n"
"\n"
"static PyMethodDef spam_methods[] = {\n"
"    {\n"
"        .ml_name=\"system\",\n"
"        .ml_meth=spam_system,\n"
"        .ml_flags=METH_O,\n"
"        .ml_doc=\"Execute a shell command.\",\n"
"    },\n"
"    {NULL, NULL, 0, NULL}        /* Sentinel */\n"
"};\n"
"\n"
"/// Module slot table\n"
"\n"
"PyABIInfo_VAR(abi_info);\n"
"\n"
"static PySlot spam_slots[] = {\n"
"    PySlot_STATIC_DATA(Py_mod_abi, &abi_info),\n"
"    PySlot_STATIC_DATA(Py_mod_name, \"spam\"),\n"
"    PySlot_STATIC_DATA(Py_mod_doc, \"A wonderful module with an example "
"function\"),\n"
"    PySlot_STATIC_DATA(Py_mod_methods, spam_methods),\n"
"    PySlot_END\n"
"};\n"
"\n"
"/// Export hook prototype\n"
"\n"
"PyMODEXPORT_FUNC PyModExport_spam(void);\n"
"\n"
"/// Module export hook\n"
"\n"
"PyMODEXPORT_FUNC\n"
"PyModExport_spam(void)\n"
"{\n"
"   return spam_slots;\n"
"}\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../extending/first-extension-module.rst:603
msgid "Appendix: Other build tools"
msgstr ""

#: ../../extending/first-extension-module.rst:605
msgid ""
"You should be able to follow this tutorial -- except the *Running your build "
"tool* section itself -- with a build tool other than ``meson-python``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../extending/first-extension-module.rst:609
msgid ""
"The Python Packaging User Guide has a `list of recommended tools <https://"
"packaging.python.org/en/latest/guides/tool-recommendations/#build-backends-"
"for-extension-modules>`_; be sure to choose one for the C language."
msgstr ""

#: ../../extending/first-extension-module.rst:614
msgid "Workaround for missing PyInit function"
msgstr ""

#: ../../extending/first-extension-module.rst:616
msgid ""
"If your build tool output complains about missing ``PyInit_spam``, add the "
"following function to your module for now:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../extending/first-extension-module.rst:619
msgid ""
"// A workaround\n"
"void *PyInit_spam(void) { return NULL; }"
msgstr ""

#: ../../extending/first-extension-module.rst:624
msgid ""
"This is a shim for an old-style :ref:`initialization function <extension-"
"export-hook>`, which was required in extension modules for CPython 3.14 and "
"below. Current CPython does not need it, but some build tools may still "
"assume that all extension modules need to define it."
msgstr ""

#: ../../extending/first-extension-module.rst:629
msgid ""
"If you use this workaround, you will get the exception ``SystemError: "
"initialization of spam failed without raising an exception`` instead of "
"``ImportError: dynamic module does not define module export function``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../extending/first-extension-module.rst:636
msgid "Compiling directly"
msgstr ""

#: ../../extending/first-extension-module.rst:638
msgid ""
"Using a third-party build tool is heavily recommended, as it will take care "
"of various details of your platform and Python installation, of naming the "
"resulting extension, and, later, of distributing your work."
msgstr ""

#: ../../extending/first-extension-module.rst:643
msgid ""
"If you are building an extension for as *specific* system, or for yourself "
"only, you might instead want to run your compiler directly. The way to do "
"this is system-specific; be prepared for issues you will need to solve "
"yourself."
msgstr ""

#: ../../extending/first-extension-module.rst:649
msgid "Linux"
msgstr "Linux"

#: ../../extending/first-extension-module.rst:651
msgid ""
"On Linux, the Python development package may include a ``python3-config`` "
"command that prints out the required compiler flags. If you use it, check "
"that it corresponds to the CPython interpreter you'll use to load the "
"module. Then, start with the following command:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../extending/first-extension-module.rst:657
msgid ""
"gcc --shared $(python3-config --cflags --ldflags) spammodule.c -o spam.so"
msgstr ""

#: ../../extending/first-extension-module.rst:661
msgid ""
"This should generate a ``spam.so`` file that you need to put in a directory "
"on :py:attr:`sys.path`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../extending/first-extension-module.rst:666
msgid "Footnotes"
msgstr "Notas de rodapé"

#: ../../extending/first-extension-module.rst:667
msgid "``spam`` is the favorite food of Monty Python fans..."
msgstr ""

#: ../../extending/first-extension-module.rst:668
msgid ""
"The source file name is entirely up to you, though some tools can be picky "
"about the ``.c`` extension. This tutorial uses the traditional ``*module.c`` "
"suffix. Some people would just use :file:`spam.c` to implement a module "
"named ``spam``, projects where Python isn't the primary language might use "
"``py_spam.c``, and so on."
msgstr ""

#: ../../extending/first-extension-module.rst:675
msgid ""
"Including :file:`stdlib.h` is technically not necessary, since :file:`Python."
"h` includes it and :ref:`several other standard headers <capi-system-"
"includes>` for its own use or for backwards compatibility. However, it is "
"good practice to explicitly include what you need."
msgstr ""

#: ../../extending/first-extension-module.rst:680
msgid ""
"The :c:type:`!PyMethodDef` structure is also used to create methods of "
"classes, so there's no separate \":c:type:`!PyFunctionDef`\"."
msgstr ""

#: ../../extending/first-extension-module.rst:683
msgid ""
"The name :c:func:`PyLong_FromLong` might not seem obvious. ``PyLong`` refers "
"to a the Python :py:class:`int`, which was originally called ``long``; the "
"``FromLong`` refers to the C ``long`` (or ``long int``) type."
msgstr ""

#: ../../extending/first-extension-module.rst:688
msgid ""
"Here, ``PyUnicode`` refers to the original name of the Python :py:class:"
"`str` class: ``unicode``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../extending/first-extension-module.rst:691
msgid ""
"The ``AndSize`` part of the name refers to the fact that this function can "
"also retrieve the size of the buffer, using an output argument. We don't "
"need this, so we set the second argument to NULL."
msgstr ""

#: ../../extending/first-extension-module.rst:694
msgid ""
"We're ignoring the fact that Python strings can also contain NUL bytes, "
"which terminate a C string. In other words, our function will treat ``spam."
"system(\"foo\\0bar\")`` as ``spam.system(\"foo\")``. This possibility can "
"lead to security issues, so the real ``os.system`` function size checks for "
"this case and raises an error."
msgstr ""
